    {
      "kind": {
        "id": "E0007",
        "name": "invalid-pattern",
        "expected": "identifier or pattern",
        "found": {
          "kind": "{",
          "text": "{"
        },
        "fix": "add a variable name, \"_\" (underscore) to ignore it.",
        "hint": "\nThe left side of a let-expression allows you to pattern match on values to assign them to variables, but also to deconstruct them and access their inner values.\n\n   ```ocaml\n   let variable = 42 in\n   let { x; _ } = point in\n   let Some x = optional in\n   (* ... *)\n   ```\n\nBeware that pattern matching on only one of many possible values will lead to runtime errors!\n"
      },
      "span": {
        "start": 390,
        "end": 390
      }
    },
    {
      "kind": {
        "id": "E0003",
        "name": "missing-let-binding-equals",
        "expected": "=",
        "found": {
          "kind": "{",
          "text": "{"
        },
        "fix": "add = between the pattern and expression",
        "hint": "Every let binding needs an = between the pattern and the expression."
      },
      "span": {
        "start": 390,
        "end": 390
      }
    },
    {
      "kind": {
        "id": "E0020",
        "name": "missing-binary-operand",
        "expected": "left operand for %",
        "found": {
          "kind": "%",
          "text": "%"
        },
        "fix": "add an expression before the operator",
        "hint": "Binary operators like +, -, *, =, etc. require both a left and right operand.\n\nFor example:\n  ```ocaml\n  let x = 1 + 2   (* correct *)\n  let y = 1 +     (* missing right operand *)\n  let z = + 2     (* missing left operand *)\n  ```\n\nIf you want to create a partially applied operator function, use parentheses:\n  ```ocaml\n  let add_one = (+) 1\n  ```\n"
      },
      "span": {
        "start": 443,
        "end": 444
      }
